TASK 4 SQL

Backup Script

Command:
mysqldump -u root -p intern_testdb > intern_testdb_backup.sql

Explanation:
- This command exports the database `intern_testdb` into a .sql file.
- It includes all tables and data.

Recovery Script

Command:
mysql -u root -p -e "CREATE DATABASE intern_testdb;"
mysql -u root -p intern_testdb < intern_testdb_backup.sql

Explanation:
- First line creates the database again if it was deleted.
- Second line restores data from the backup file.

 Documentation of the Process

Create Test Database and Table

CREATE DATABASE intern_testdb;

USE intern_testdb;

CREATE TABLE students (
  id INT PRIMARY KEY AUTO_INCREMENT,
  name VARCHAR(50),
  email VARCHAR(100)
);

INSERT INTO students (name, email) VALUES
('Alice', 'alice@example.com'),
('Bob', 'bob@example.com');


Backup the Database

Run the backup command:

mysqldump -u root -p intern_testdb > intern_testdb_backup.sql


Simulate Data Loss

Drop the database (to simulate failure):

DROP DATABASE intern_testdb;


Restore the Database

Run recovery commands:

mysql -u root -p -e "CREATE DATABASE intern_testdb;"
mysql -u root -p intern_testdb < intern_testdb_backup.sql


Verify the Restoration

USE intern_testdb;
SELECT * FROM students;
